and photofission cross sections for 235U, 236U, 238U,
and 232Th.

x4codes.hlp: Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, CA, United States of America

x4freetext: Positron annihilation in flight.
Photon energy resolution ranged from about 250 keV at
energies below 10 MeV to about 325 keV at the highest
energy (about 18 MeV).
The target specifications are given in previously
published work, J.T.Caldwell, et al., Nuc.Sci.Eng.,73
The neutron detector consists of a 61-cm cube
of paraffin moderator in which 48 51-cm long BF3
proportional counters are embeded. The latter are
arranged in an array of four coaxial rings, each
containing 12 counters, cylindrically symmetric about
the beam line.
Direct photoneutron detection.
Ring-ratio neutron multiplicity measurement.
The effective neutron detection system permits direct,
separate and simultaneous measurements of the partial
cross sections: (gamma,n)+(gamma,np), (gamma,2n), etc
After the recorded neutron events were corrected for
pileup in the detector, the neutron backgrounds
(annihilation target removed) were substracted for
both the positron and electron measurements.
Because the energy spectrum of the annihilation-plus-
Bremsstrahlung radiation differs from that of purely
Bremsstrahlung photons, a measured correction was
applied to the ion-chamber (beam monitor) response to
normalize the electron data to the positron data.
Multiplication effects in the samples were determined
both by Monte Carlo calculations and by measurements
with samples wrapped in thin cadmium metal foil; such
effects necessitated small corrections to the data of
respectively. uncertainties resulting from these
corrections are estimated to be less than 1% in all
cases.
The normalized electron data then were substracted fro
the positron data, leaving the neutron counts which
result only from the annihilation radiation.
The measured sample-blank data, normalized to equal
photon flux, were substracted from the target data to
give the net target results.
After a small correction for the neutron multiplicity
in each ring, the data were corrected for the energy-
dependent efficiency of the neutron detector using th
ring-ratio result for each energy.
The data were converted to photoneutron cross sections
by applying the measured ion-chamber response per
photon, the known number of target nuclei in the beam
and a small correction for the photon attenuation in
the sample.
Statistical errors only.
Systematic uncertainties arising from the
substraction of the positron-Bremsstrahlung yields,
from the neutron-detector efficiency calibration, and
from the photon-flux calibration are about 2, 3, and
5%, respectively. The final cross section values are
subject to overall systematic uncertainties that do
not exceed 7%.
Information extracted from the data includes integrate
cross sections and their moments, giant-resonance
parameters, deformation and radius parameters, and
relative and absolute neutron and fission
probabilities.

Dates, SUBENTs 030 - 033 addition.
